82. sedeat. It is certain that in the time of Plautus there was no sitting accommodatiori in the Roman theatres; yet we find even in undoubtedly Plautine passages (e. g. Aul. iv. 9. ὁ) references to a sitting public. We must therefore suppose that the spectators either brought with them stools and- chairs, or seated themselves on the ground. Val. Maximus says distinctly (ii. 4. 2), that in the censorship of Messalla and Cassius (599), when it was proposed to erect a stone theatre, the proposal was rejected on the motion of Scipio Nasica: atque etiam Scto cautum est ne quis in urbe propiusue passus mille subsellza posuisse sedensue ludos spectare uellet, ut scilicet remissioni animorum standi uirilitas propria Romanae gentis iuncta esset. The Theatrum Pompei, the first stone theatre, was built just a hundred years after this Sctum.
